PK, ab main Caching ko exactly tumhare framework me samjhaunga:

Evolution of Pain

The Cure

What-If Sandbox

Real-World Analogy

HLD Data Flow

Isse concept feel aayega, sirf definitions nahi.

1️⃣ Evolution of Pain (Nightmare Scenario)

Imagine ek popular website hai.

Architecture:

Users → App Server → Database

Example:

1M users

Har request database ko hit kar rahi hai.

🚨 Disaster 1 — Slow Database

Database read time:

DB read = 100ms

Agar 1M requests aaye:

1M × 100ms

System slow.

User experience:

Page load = 2-3 seconds

Bad UX.

🚨 Disaster 2 — Database Overload

Sab requests DB pe ja rahi hain.

Users → App → DB
Users → App → DB
Users → App → DB

DB CPU spike.

DB overloaded

Crash possibility.

🚨 Disaster 3 — Same Data Repeatedly

Example:

Product details
User profile
Homepage data

Ye data frequently read hota hai.

Phir bhi har baar DB hit.

Waste of resources.

Pain Summary

Without caching:

❌ High DB load
❌ High latency
❌ Poor scalability
❌ Slow system
2️⃣ The Cure — Caching

Hero:

Cache

Architecture:

Users
  ↓
App Server
  ↓
Cache
  ↓
Database

Flow:

1️⃣ App first cache check karta hai
2️⃣ Agar data mil gaya → fast response
3️⃣ Agar nahi mila → DB se fetch
4️⃣ Cache me store

Core Idea

Cache =

fast memory

Example technologies:

Redis
Memcached

Memory speed:

RAM read = ~1ms
DB read = ~100ms

100× faster.

3️⃣ Distributed Caching

Problem:

Single cache server.

App → Cache → DB

Problems:

Single point of failure
Limited memory

Solution:

Cache cluster

Architecture:

App Servers
     │
Cache Client
     │
Cache Pool
 ┌───┼───┐
Cache1 Cache2 Cache3

Data distribute hota hai using:

Consistent Hashing
4️⃣ Caching Strategies

System design me ye very important hai.

🔹 1 Cache-Aside

Most common.

Flow:

Client → App
         ↓
       Cache?
Case 1 — Cache Hit
Cache → Data

Return immediately.

Case 2 — Cache Miss
App → DB
App → Cache
Return to client

Sequence:

Read request
→ Cache miss
→ DB read
→ Save in cache
Pros
Read heavy systems
Flexible cache structure
Cache failure safe

Example:

Product catalog
User profile
Problem

Cache inconsistency.

Example:

DB value = 11
Cache value = 10

User gets stale data.

🔹 2 Read-Through Cache

Difference:

Cache khud DB read karta hai.

Flow:

App → Cache
Cache → DB

Application ko DB access karna nahi padta.

Pros
Application logic simple
Cache automatically manage
Problem

Cache structure same as DB.

Customization possible nahi.

🔹 3 Write-Around Cache

Write directly DB me.

Write → DB

Cache update nahi hota.

But cache invalidate ho jata hai.

Example:

Cache marked dirty

Next read:

Cache miss
→ DB read
→ Update cache
Pros
Cache consistency improve
Problem

New data always cache miss.

🔹 4 Write-Through Cache

Write flow:

App → Cache → DB

Both update simultaneously.

Pros
Cache always fresh
No stale data
Problem

Latency increase.

Because:

2 writes

Cache + DB.

Also:

Two phase commit needed
🔹 5 Write-Back (Write-Behind)

Most advanced.

Flow:

Write → Cache
Write → Queue
Queue → DB (async)

Architecture:

Client
  ↓
App
  ↓
Cache
  ↓
Queue
  ↓
Database
Advantage

Very fast writes.

Example:

Social media likes
Analytics counters

Latency:

< 1ms
Fault Tolerance

Even if DB down:

Cache still serves data
Queue stores writes

Later DB update.

Problem

Data loss risk.

Example:

Cache TTL expire before DB write.

5️⃣ What-If Sandbox

Interview thinking.

❓ What if cache remove kar diya?

System becomes:

App → DB

Problems:

High DB load
Slow performance
❓ What if write-back cache but queue fail?

Writes lost.

Cache updated
DB not updated

Data inconsistency.

❓ What if cache TTL small?

Data frequently expire.

Result:

Many cache misses
DB overload
6️⃣ Real-World Analogy

Imagine library desk.

Library storage room:

Database

Front desk bookshelf:

Cache

Flow:

Student asks book

Step 1:

Check front desk

If present:

Give immediately

If not:

Go to storage room
Bring book
Keep copy at desk

Exactly caching.

7️⃣ HLD Diagram (What you should draw)

Interview architecture:

Users
   │
   ▼
Load Balancer
   │
   ▼
Application Servers
   │
   ▼
Redis Cache Cluster
   │
   ▼
Database

For write-back:

App → Cache → Message Queue → DB
Final Intuition

Cache is used when:

Reads >> Writes

Goal:

Reduce DB load
Reduce latency
Increase scalability